CHIN music is when a pitcher in baseball intentionally throws the ball high and inside to the batter, so that it goes inches from his CHIN.  It (understandably) freaks out the batter, who doesn't want to get hit in the face by a hard object traveling at 95 mph.  The batter will generally move a bit farther from home plate in the BATTERS' BOX and perhaps become a bit "gun SHY".

For more CHIN-wagging tales, ask a baseball fan about the story of Tony Conigliaro.

@Beth in Greenbelt

Chin music in baseball is when a batter is crowding the plate (standing too close to home in the batter's box) and the pitcher wants to send the batter a message.  

So he throws a pitch on the inside corner of the strike zone (or just outside of it) at chin level.  That usually gets the batter to step back a little.

